<h1 class="text-4xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 mb-4">CLI Usage & Evolution</h1>
<p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">How to safely use the GO-DUCK Generator without destroying your manual Go code edits over time.</p>

<section class="mb-10">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-4 border-b pb-2">1. The Command Pipeline</h2>
    <p class="mb-4">The GO-DUCK-CLI operates on basically two commands. The initialization of your system, and the continuous evolution pipeline.</p>
    
    <pre><code class="language-bash"># Command 1: Fresh Creation
# Scaffold an entirely new ecosystem. This generates ALL baseline infrastructure.
go-duck create -o ./MY_APP -c config.yaml -g initial_schema.gdl

# Command 2: Incremental Stateful Update
# Used whenever you modify your GDL (add an entity, drop a column, add a link)
go-duck import-gdl my_new_schema.gdl -o ./MY_APP</code></pre>
</section>

<section class="mb-10">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-4 border-b pb-2">2. Persistence Intelligence & the `.go-duck/` Folder</h2>
    <p class="mb-4">"If I run the generator twice, will it overwrite my database migrations?" <strong>No.</strong></p>
    
    <p class="mb-4">The generator maintains a stateful snapshot of every entity it has ever generated inside the hidden <code>.go-duck/</code> directory at the root of your target project. When you run <code>import-gdl</code>, the code parser literally diffs your new file against the JSON representations in <code>.go-duck/</code> to intelligently assess the exact Table changes necessary without executing ghost migrations.</p>

    <div class="bg-red-50 border-l-4 border-red-500 p-4 mb-6 rounded-r">
        <p class="text-red-900"><strong>Never delete `.go-duck/`</strong> unless you are intentionally wiping the database and starting configuration completely from zero.</p>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="mb-10">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-4 border-b pb-2">3. JHipster-Style "Needles" (Safe Code Injection)</h2>
    <p class="mb-4">"If I write custom endpoints in `main.go`, will running the generator wipe them out?" <strong>No, if you use Needles!</strong></p>
    
    <p class="mb-4">The generator utilizes carefully placed HTML-style comments called "needles". For example, inside <code>main.go</code>, you will see markers like <code>// go-duck-needle-add-init-server</code>.</p>
    
    <p class="mb-4">When the generator runs an incremental update, it doesn't just overwrite <code>main.go</code> via a template. It opens the <em>existing</em> <code>main.go</code> file on your computer, finds the Needle anchor via REGEX, and safely injects the new Code Block just below it!</p>

    <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2 mt-6">Active Needle Locations:</h3>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 mb-4 text-gray-700 font-mono text-sm bg-gray-100 p-4 rounded">
        <li>// go-duck-needle-add-import (main.go)</li>
        <li>// go-duck-needle-add-init-repository (main.go)</li>
        <li>// go-duck-needle-add-grpc-service (internal/server/grpc.go)</li>
    </ul>

    <p class="text-gray-600 italic">As long as you leave these comment markers intact in their original structure, your manual custom business logic will never be touched by GO-DUCK.</p>
</section>
